I have taken a general look at the organic task allocation mechanism.
I think it is reasonable to restore the way that all miners get organic tasks fairly.

Let me tell you my reasons:
1. Registering a key itself has a cost, and only miners with matching strength (such as a sufficient number of GPUs) will keep registering. The more keys there are, the more GPUs are needed to maintain the success rate and TPS.

2. The mechanism for miners with low success rate/low pass rate (referring to the verification of the test) to reduce organic tasks is reasonable. However, the open route task should prevent miners from caching. Miners caching questions and answers, is it really what the real customers of Targon Hub need? Is it really beneficial to the development of Targon? Shouldn't our direction of progress be on faster model output (referring to the actual operation of the GPU to answer questions, not caching). The current competition seems to have become how to cache the open route tasks to improve the pass rate.

3. If the head miners continue to get all. In fact, all miners will start to cheat. If you don't cheat, you will lose everything. If this continues, I will continue to look for loopholes, and Subnet 4 will become a game of finding loopholes. Whoever can make good use of the mechanism and have a good relationship with the owner/validator will have an advantage.
